020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/16/covid-19-125-new-cases-recorded-bring-total-number-to-553|title=Covid-19: 125 new cases recorded, bringing total number to 553|work=The Star|date=16 March 2020|accessdate=16 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316102311/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/16/covid-19-125-new-cases-recorded-bring-total-number-to-553|archive-date=16 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 17 March, Malaysia reported its first two deaths from the coronavirus, a 60-year-old priest from Emmanuel Baptist Church in [[Kuching]], Sarawak and a 34-year-old participant of the Muslim religious gathering in Sri Petaling from Johor Bahru, [[Johor]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://says.com/my/news/breaking-60-year-old-pastor-in-kuching-is-first-covid-19-death-in-malaysia|title=[BREAKING] Malaysia Records 2 Deaths Caused By COVID-19 Pandemic|last=Vin Ang|first=May|work=Says.com|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=17 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317105528/https://says.com/my/news/breaking-60-year-old-pastor-in-kuching-is-first-covid-19-death-in-malaysia|archive-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> A total of 673 cases were reported by 17 March,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/03/17/covid-19-120-new-cases-reported-in-malaysia-today-95-related-to-tabligh-gat/1847483|title=Covid-19: 120 new cases reported in Malaysia today, 95 related to tabligh gathering cluster|last=Tee|first=Kenneth|work=Says.com|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=19 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319010034/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/03/17/covid-19-120-new-cases-reported-in-malaysia-today-95-related-to-tabligh-gat/1847483|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and an additional 117 new cases were diagnosed on 18 March, with 11 discharged, bringing the cumulative statistic for positive and recovered cases to 790 and 60 respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/19/covid-19-117-new-cases-total-rises-to-790-in-malaysia/|title=Covid-19: 117 new cases, total rises to 790 in Malaysia|work=Bernama|via=Borneo Post|date=19 March 2020|accessdate=19 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319010257/https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/19/covid-19-117-new-cases-total-rises-to-790-in-malaysia/|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 19 March, Health Director Noor Hisham once again urged people to stay home, saying that Malaysia has a small chance of blocking the rapid spread of coronavirus disease as compared to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Italy|current situation]] facing by Italy; telling that if it misses the third wave of infection, the situation will be out of control similar to what happened in Italy. It is also very likely that the government will extend the \"movement restriction order\" for another 14 days.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sinchew.com.my/content/content_2236821.html|title=\u5927\u9a6c\u963b\u65ad\u51a0\u75c5\u8fc5\u901f\u4f20\u64ad\u7387\u5c0f\u00b7\u536b\u751f\u603b\u76d1\uff1a\u653f\u5e9c\u53ef\u80fd\u5ef6\u957f\u7ba1\u5236\u4ee4|trans-title=Malaysia to block rapid spread of crown disease, Health Director: Government may extend control order|language=Chinese|work=Sin Chew Daily|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=19 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319010628/https://www.sinchew.com.my/content/content_2236821.html|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The Prime Minister also has similarly appeal to every Malaysians to adhere the control order to prevent further infections within the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theedgemarkets.com/article/just-stay-home-muhyiddin-appeals-malaysians|title=Just stay at home, Muhyiddin appeals to Malaysians|last=Zainul|first=Emir|work=The Edge Markets|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=19 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.arc